The purpose of this safety study is to evaluate existing safety performance and identify potential
countermeasures to reduce traffic crashes at the intersection of State Route 615 (Center Street) and Tyler
Boulevard (CR 516) in Mentor, Ohio. The study intersection is located on State Route 615 at log point
4.45, 1300 feet south of the State Route 2 interchange. A project location map is provided in Figure 1.
The Center Street/Tyler Boulevard intersection is ranked #46 on the Ohio Department of Transportation
(ODOT) 2011 Urban Intersection Peak Searching Excess Locations listing. A review of crash data
provided by the ODOT yielded a total of 103 reported crashes within the intersection influence area
during a 3-year period between 2009 and 2011. Of the total reported crashes, 24.3 percent resulted in
injury, which is just less than the statewide average of 25.7 percent for injury crashes on state route, non-
freeway locations. No fatalities occurred during the study period.
The following crash types and conditions are over represented at the Center Street/Tyler Boulevard
intersection compared to statewide averages (shown in parenthesis). Note the statewide crash averages are
based on 2007-2011 data whereas the project data encompasses years 2009 to 2011.
Road condition – Wet: 26 crashes or 25.2 percent
State Route 615, herein referred to as Center Street, is a north/south roadway that serves as a primary
arterial corridor for the city of Mentor. Grade-separated interchanges provide access from Center Street
to the two major freeways in the area: Lakeland Freeway (State Route 2) and Interstate 90. A section of
Center Street just north of Tyler Boulevard was under construction in 2011 to increase capacity at the
State Route 2 interchange. This project did not include upgrades at the Tyler Boulevard intersection.
Center Street (State Route 615) is classified by ODOT as an Urban Principal Arterial facility that is a
designated route on the National Highway System. The posted speed limit on Center Street is 35 miles
per hour. Average daily traffic volume on Center Street ranged between 23,800 vehicles per day (south of
Tyler Boulevard) to 28,850 vehicles per day (north of Tyler Boulevard).
Center Street features two northbound and two southbound through lanes at the Tyler Boulevard
intersection. For the majority of the day, the southbound curb lane serves as a shared through/right turn
lane. From 7:40 AM to 8:10 AM an overhead-mounted, changeable lane use sign designates the
southbound curb lane for right turns only. There are single left turn lanes in both directions on Center
Street. Pavement adjacent to the left turn lanes is a painted median with transverse hatching. Lane widths
on Center Street vary between 11 feet in the turn lanes and inside through lanes and 15 feet in the curb
Tyler Boulevard (C.R. 516) is classified by ODOT as an Urban Minor Arterial that is not a designated
route on the National Highway System. The posted speed limit on Tyler Boulevard is 35 miles per hour
through the study intersection. Average daily traffic volume on Tyler Boulevard ranges between 12,400
vehicles per day (west of Center Street) and 13,000 vehicles per day (east of Center Street).
Tyler Boulevard is a four-lane roadway section that widens to provide additional capacity at the Center
Street intersection. Just east of the intersection, Tyler Boulevard transitions to a two-lane typical section.
The lane configuration of the eastbound Tyler Boulevard approach features dual left turn lanes, a single
through lane, and a single right turn lane (L-L-T-R). The lane configuration of the westbound approach
features a single left turn lane, a single through lane, and a single right turn lane (L-T-R). Lane widths on
Existing roadway conditions are shown graphically in Figure 2 with a detailed existing condition diagram
A noteworthy feature of the Center Street/Tyler Boulevard intersection is the placement of driveway
access points within the influence area of the intersection. The functional area of an intersection is defined
as the area beyond the physical intersection of two roadways and includes two components: one upstream
of the physical area of the intersection and one downstream as shown in Figure 3. The upstream (or
intersection approach) includes the distance needed for decision-making, maneuvering, and required
vehicle storage. The downstream area consists of a conflict overlap distance that allows a through vehicle
to clear the intersection and any downstream conflict points. The downstream distance is calculated to be
250 feet based on a design speed of 35 MPH
In an attempt to reduce conflicts caused by turning movements and vehicle queues at driveways within
the intersection influence area, signs have been installed at the following locations to prohibit left turn
movements. None of the left turn prohibitions are enforced with physical features such as concrete islands
Northbound Center Street (north of Tyler Blvd.): Left turns are prohibited from Center Street
into the commercial properties on the west side of Center Street. No Left Turn signs are ground
mounted and overhead mounted on the back side of the overhead sign support.
Speedway access on Center Street: Left turns are prohibited from the Speedway, located in the
northeast quadrant of the intersection. Signs are ground mounted.
Westbound Tyler Boulevard (west of Center Street): Left turns are prohibited from Tyler
Boulevard to the Fiat site located in the southwest quadrant of the intersection. Left turns are also
prohibited from the Fiat driveway onto Center Street. This driveway is intended to function as a
Best Friends Restaurant access on Center Street: Left turns are prohibited from the southern-
most driveway of the Best Friends Restaurant driveway to Center Street. This site is located on
the west side of Center Street, north of Tyler Boulevard (adjacent to El Rodeo Restaurant).
Access points within the intersection influence area can negatively affect safety. An increased level of
driver attention is required to process potential conflicts with vehicles entering or leaving access points
near an intersection. This diverts the driver’s attention from the primary task of navigation at a signalized
The Center Street intersection with Tyler Boulevard is controlled by a traffic signal operating an eight-
phase signal sequence. The traffic signal is a mast arm design with supports located in each of the four
quadrants of the intersection. Left turn phases are actuated with video detection. Existing signal phasing is
summarized below with existing signal timing summarized in Table 1.
Northbound Center Street left turn phase is a leading protected/permissive
Southbound Center Street left turn phase is a leading protected/permissive
Southbound Center Street right turn overlap with the EB left turn phase
Eastbound Tyler Boulevard left turn phase is a protected only (dual left turn)
Westbound Tyler Boulevard left turn phase is a leading protected/permissive
Pedestrian pushbuttons are provided for all pedestrian phases (no recalled ped movements)

During peak hours, northbound traffic on Center Street destined to eastbound Lakeland Freeway

Crosswalks are present to cross all four legs of the intersection. Sidewalk is present along both
sides of Center Street and both sides of the east leg of Tyler Boulevard. There is no sidewalk on
Tyler Boulevard west of the Center Street intersection.
Pedestrian pushbuttons are provided in all four quadrants of the intersection. However, the
pushbutton in the southeast quadrant to cross the south leg of Center Street was not functioning.
There is a pole-mounted Pedestrian Crossing sign located on Tyler Boulevard just east of the
Center Street intersection, viewed by eastbound traffic leaving the intersection. This sign is not
accompanied by a marked crosswalk nor is there any pedestrian signing for the opposite approach

Crash data was furnished by the Ohio Department of Transportation for the Center Street intersection
with Tyler Boulevard, encompassing a three-year study period between January 1, 2009 and December
31, 2011. The OH-1 report for each documented crash was reviewed to confirm accuracy and to locate
crashes properly within the study limits. Crash diagrams for the intersection are included in Appendix D.
Noteworthy crash statistics for the three-year period between 2009 and 2011 are summarized below and
in Graphs 2 and 3. Statewide averages for crashes on state system, non-freeway locations are shown in
parentheses based on data for years 2007 through 2011. Of the total reported crashes, 24.3 percent
resulted in injury, which is comparable to the statewide average of 25.7 percent for injury crashes on a
Road condition – Wet: 26 crashes or 25.2 percent
A review of observed and documented crash history at the Center Street/Tyler Boulevard intersection
suggests patterns that are consistent with high-volume urban/suburban corridors that experience a high
level of congestion coupled with uncontrolled access points. Prevalent crash patterns are described below:
Crash frequencies in both 2010 and 2011 were 50 percent greater than in 2009. Crash frequency
remained constant in 2010 and 2011. The increase in crashes in 2010 and 2011 may be
attributable to construction on Center Street near the S.R. 2 interchange.
The majority of crashes (73%) occurred between the hours of 11AM and 7PM. The highest
frequency of crashes occurred during the noon hour (17 of 103 crashes, or 17%). See Graph 2.
The majority of crashes (52%) were rear end crashes (See Graph 3), which is consistent with the
finding that 57% involved a vehicle that was slowing or stopped in traffic. The percent of injuries
(24%) is slightly lower than the statewide average, which suggests lower operating speeds
There were 32 angle and left turn crashes, representing 31% of all crashes at the intersection. The
majority of these crash types involved vehicles turning to/from the driveway access points located

The three most prevalent crash types reported at the study intersection were rear end, angle (right angle
and left turn crashes), and sideswipe passing crashes, accounting for 98 percent of the total intersection
crashes. These crash types were distributed on the intersection approaches as summarized in Table 3.
Noteworthy crash patterns within the intersection influence area are summarized below:
Center Street - Northbound: Rear end crashes are the primary crash type on northbound Center
Street. 16 rear end crashes occurred on the northbound approach to the Tyler Boulevard
intersection, the majority of which involved vehicles in the curb lane. An additional 13 rear end
crashes occurred north of Tyler Boulevard intersection, attributable to the vehicles turning right
into the Sunoco access driveway as well as queues presumably extending from the SR 2
interchange. Some of these rear end crashes may have been mitigated by the recent upstream
capacity improvements on Center Street at the SR 2 interchange.
Center Street – Southbound: Crash patterns on the southbound Center Street approach are less
pronounced, with a scattering of various crash types.
There were a total of 10 SB rear end crashes with 5 occurring in the SB left turn lane. The
rear end crashes in the SB left turn lane occurred during the 7AM, 8AM and 2 PM hours.
The demand for the SB left turn movement is high during the typical day time hours and
this pattern of crashes may be attributable to oversaturated conditions and/or insufficient
11 crashes were attributed to the Speedway driveway on the east side of Center Street.
These crash types included right angle, turning angle, rear end and sideswipe but were all
attributable to vehicles turning into or out of the Speedway driveway. There were no
crashes attributed to the driveway on the west side of Center Street where turn prohibition
Tyler Boulevard – Eastbound: The three crash types documented on the eastbound Tyler
Boulevard approach included rear end, sideswipe, and angle crashes.
There were 10 EB rear end crashes on Tyler Boulevard. Most crashes occurred during
mid-day (11am-2 pm) and evening peak (4pm-6pm) periods when volumes peak and
There were 7 EB sideswipe (passing) crashes on Tyler Boulevard, most of which
involved EB left turning vehicles. The existing condition terminates the inside EB
through lane on Tyler Boulevard as an exclusive left turn lane at the Center Street
intersection. Narrow lane widths (10 feet) coupled with limited delineation of the left turn
lanes may be a contributing factor.
There were 3 angle crashes attributable to the Fiat access driveway on Tyler Boulevard.
This driveway is signed for no left turns from Tyler Blvd to the Fiat site but there are no
physical features preventing the left turn movement.
Tyler Boulevard – Westbound: The prevalent crash pattern on the westbound Tyler Boulevard
approach to Center Street are crashes attributed to vehicles making left turns to and from the
Speedway access driveway on Tyler Boulevard (left turn, turning angle and right turn).
The following countermeasures are recommended to address contributing factors associated with the
prevalent crash types at the Center Street/Tyler Boulevard intersection. Additional countermeasures are
recommended to minimize potential safety issues that may not be directly attributable to historical crash
trends. A conceptual plan included as Figure 4 shows the proposed short term countermeasures.
Supporting technical documentation for the proposed countermeasures is included in Appendix C

page.text: 1. Manage access on the east leg of Tyler Boulevard: The Speedway driveway on Tyler
Boulevard is located only 100 feet from the stop line for the westbound approach to Center Street.
This driveway location is the primary contributing factor in 15 angle crashes (left turn, right angle
and turning angle). Construction of a raised median on the east leg of Tyler Boulevard would be
desirable to reduce vehicular conflict points within the intersection influence area. A raised
median, while effective is not recommended for the following reasons:
Fuel truck deliveries enter the Speedway site from the Tyler Boulevard access point.
Damages may be incurred if fuel deliveries to the site are impacted.
A raised median would require pavement widening on the south side of Tyler Boulevard.
Property is not available from the Speedway site without risk of damages due to changes to
The alternative to pavement widening is lane width reduction on Tyler Boulevard. The
horizontal curvature of Tyler Boulevard and truck traffic support normal lane widths.
A alternative, short-term countermeasure is to paint a box at the Speedway access point to
encourage drivers on Tyler Boulevard not to block the Speedway driveway. Figure 4 shows an
excerpt from the Manual of Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD, 2009) of Do Not Block
Intersection markings. Crash mitigation potential: 15 crashes (left turn, right angle, and
FIGURE 4: DO NOT BLOCK INTERSECTION EXAMPLE
2. Restrict access on the north leg of Center Street: Construction of a raised median using a
bollard design (Figure 5) on the north leg of Center Street is recommended to reduce vehicular
conflict points within the intersection influence area. The Speedway driveway on Center Street is
located approximately 100 feet from the Tyler Boulevard intersection. This driveway location is
the primary contributing factor in 11 angle and sideswipe crashes. A raised median in this
location also provides a physical barrier to prevent vehicles from making left turns to and from
the business driveways on the west side of Center Street. Crash mitigation potential: 11
FIGURE 5: DO NOT BLOCK INTERSECTION EXAMPLE
3. Increase capacity of the Center/Tyler intersection: Capacity deficiencies at the Center/Tyler
intersection contribute to peak hour congestion and an overall decrease in safety. Increasing
intersection capacity is recommended by adding an additional northbound through lane on Center
Street that extends from the Lindsay Drive intersection to the start of the northbound right turn
lane at the eastbound SR 2 interchange. With this improvement, overall intersection delay is
decreased from 112.0 seconds to 64.7 seconds during the PM peak hour (LOS F to LOS E). A
concept plan of the proposed improvements is shown in Figure 6. Details of the capacity analysis
are included in Appendix C. Crash mitigation potential: all non-driveway crashes.
4. Upgrade pavement markings: This recommendation includes the following components:
Reapply crosswalk lines on all legs of the intersection
Reapply dotted lines for turning movements of dual left turn lanes through the intersection
(eastbound Tyler Boulevard). This countermeasure is targeted to mitigate 7 sideswipe crashes
associated with eastbound left turn movements.
Improved delineation of the EB left turn lanes is recommended in conjunction with the
alignment modification of the EB approach. It is also recommended that the width of the EB
left turn lanes be increased to a minimum of 11 feet. These countermeasures are targeted to
mitigate 7 sideswipe crashes associated with eastbound left turn movements. Increasing the
lanes widths on the eastbound approach will eliminate one of the two westbound receiving
lanes. The removal of a westbound receiving lane will not affect intersection capacity since
no dual lanes feed the southbound movement.
5. Upgrade traffic signal installation: Upgrades to the traffic signal are recommended in
conjunction with the proposed capacity improvements discussed above. This recommendation
includes the following components and has a potential to mitigate all non-driveway crashes.
Update clearance intervals. Modify the yellow clearance and all red clearance times per
ODOT Traffic Engineering Manual and ITE guidelines, as summarized in Appendix E.
Recommended clearance intervals are based on posted speeds (35 MPH) and actual crossing
Install reflective back plates on all signal heads.

The following improvements are proposed for short term implementation to address potential
Remove the pedestrian crossing sign on the east leg of Tyler Boulevard. Further evaluate

Add overhead lane use signs for the northbound Center Street approach to assist motorists

Rate of return (ROR) is an economic analysis tool to determine the financial benefits of a project based on
net present value (NPV) of an improvement. ROR values greater than zero indicate a positive return on
the original investment. Preferred countermeasures are those having the highest net present value (NPV).
Rate of return was calculated based on crash mitigation effects of the following improvements:
An additional NB through lane on Center Street from Lindsay Drive to connect with the 3
northbound lanes recently constructed north of Tyler Boulevard. Based the auditor’s tax map
information, right of way is anticipated on the east side of Center Street north of Tyler Boulevard
to accommodate this improvement. This countermeasure will potentially mitigate all non-
driveway crashes by increasing intersection capacity and throughput on Center Street.
There are no CMFs available that capture the safety benefits of installing an additional through
lane on a major street. To account for the crash mitigation potential of the additional capacity, the
CMF for “Install right turn lane” was selected and applied only to rear end crashes at the
Restrict access on Center Street (north of Tyler Boulevard) using a raised median with bollard
treatment approximately 225 feet in length. The countermeasure will mitigate driveway related
crashes on Center Street (left turn, right angle, turning angle, and sideswipe). The CMF for
“Install raised median” was applied to left turn, right angle, turning angle and sideswipe crashes
attributable to the Speedway driveway on Center Street.
Control the Speedway access driveway on Tyler Boulevard with signing and a painted box on the
pavement to designate a “no blocking” area at the driveway. This treatment is intended to
communicate to motorists on Tyler Boulevard to stop in advance of the painted area to provide
space for vehicles to make left turns to and from the Speedway driveway. This treatment is an
alternative to a raised median. The CMF for “Install raised median” was applied to left turn, right
angle, and turning angle crashes attributable to the Speedway driveway on Tyler Boulevard.
Although the painted box treatment in not a physical barrier, it is expected to have a similar
mitigative effect on those crash types.

Intersections are graded using a level of service (LOS) designation expressed in terms of letter grades. Level
of service is a quality measure describing operational conditions with a traffic stream with LOS A
representing the highest quality traffic flow and minimal delay, and LOS F representing poor traffic
operations, significant delay, and substantial queuing. Level of service is defined in terms of vehicle delay, as
published in the Highway Capacity Manual (Transportation Research Board, 2010). Levels of service
thresholds for signalized intersections have been summarized in Table A.

The National Cooperative Highway Research Program (NCHRP) Report 731: Guidelines for Timing Yellow
and All-Red Intervals at Signalized Intersections was published July 2012. A number of conclusions were
reached as a result of the comprehensive study that is important to the safety performance of signalized
The Institute of Transportation Engineers (ITE) Proposed Recommended Practice for the calculation
of yellow change intervals and all-red clearance intervals is the methodology used by the highest
percentage of state and local agencies.
Drivers were documented to decelerate when turning at an intersection. The NCHRP Report 731
recommended using a design speed of 20 mile per hour for the calculation of all red timing.
Research conducted by the North Carolina Department of Transportation published by the ITE
Journal determined that the average operating speed for left turning traffic is 17 miles per hour.
Using the current ITE guidelines to calculate the duration of yellow change and red clearance
intervals has been shown to reduce total crashes between 8 and 14 percent while reducing injury
Using the current ITE guidelines to calculate the duration of yellow change and red clearance
intervals has been shown to reduce red light running occurrences between 36 and 50 percent.
